{"type":"message","id":"674d4774","parentId":"6baf0e0c","timestamp":"2026-05-14T00:57:18.264Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_NQltOnFwsFWGoIIhuIdd9EUq|fc_094b6994f4566fc6016a051debf1d881949672bd54ba8fe21b","toolName":"exec","content":[{"type":"text","text":"/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/gateway/configuration.md:492:    See [Multi-Agent](/concepts/multi-agent) and [full reference](/gateway/config-agents#multi-agent-routing) for binding rules and per-agent access profiles.\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/gateway/configuration.md:577:| Gateway server      | `gateway.*` (port, bind, auth, tailscale, TLS, HTTP)              | **Yes**         |\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/gateway/gateway-lock.md:19:- The gateway then binds the HTTP/WebSocket listener (default `ws://127.0.0.1:18789`) using an exclusive TCP listener.\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/gateway/gateway-lock.md:32:- The macOS app still maintains its own lightweight PID guard before spawning the gateway; the runtime lock is enforced by the lock file plus HTTP/WebSocket bind.\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/gateway/discovery.md:22:- **Gateway WS (control plane)**: the WebSocket endpoint on `127.0.0.1:18789` by default; can be bound to LAN/tailnet via `gateway.bind`.\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/gateway/discovery.md:98:- `gateway.bind` in `~/.openclaw/openclaw.json` controls the Gateway bind mode.\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/gateway/trusted-proxy-auth.md:68:    bind: \"lan\",\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/gateway/trusted-proxy-auth.md:187:        bind: \"lan\",\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/gateway/trusted-proxy-auth.md:221:        bind: \"lan\",\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/gateway/trusted-proxy-auth.md:253:        bind: \"lan\",\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/gateway/trusted-proxy-auth.md:285:        bind: \"lan\",\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/gateway/security/audit-checks.md:37:| `gateway.bind_no_auth`                                        | critical      | Remote bind without shared secret                                                    | `gateway.bind`, `gateway.auth.*`                                                                     | no       |\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/gateway/security/audit-checks.md:49:| `gateway.control_ui.host_header_origin_fallback`              | warn/critical | Enables Host-header origin fallback (DNS rebinding hardening downgrade)              | `gateway.controlUi.dangerouslyAllowHostHeaderOriginFallback`                                         | no       |\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/gateway/security/audit-checks.md:62:| `discovery.mdns_full_mode`                                    | warn/critical | mDNS full mode advertises `cliPath`/`sshPort` metadata on local network              | `discovery.mdns.mode`, `gateway.bind`                                                                | no       |\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/gateway/security/index.md:163:    bind: \"loopback\",\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/gateway/security/index.md:259:`gateway.bind_no_auth` or `tools.exec.security_full_configured`). Common\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/gateway/security/index.md:263:- `gateway.*` — bind mode, auth, Tailscale, Control UI, trusted-proxy setup.\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/gateway/security/index.md:739:- `gateway.bind: \"loopback\"` (default): only local clients can connect.\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/gateway/security/index.md:1073:    bind: \"loopback\",\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/gateway/security/index.md:1277:2. **Close exposure:** set `gateway.bind: \"loopback\"` (or disable Tailscale Funnel/Serve) until you understand what happened.\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/gateway/security/index.md:1290:3. Review recent config changes (anything that could have widened access: `gateway.bind`, `gateway.auth`, dm/group policies, `tools.elevated`, plugin changes).\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/gateway/configuration-reference.md:361:    bind: \"loopback\",\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/gateway/configuration-reference.md:431:- **Legacy bind aliases**: use bind mode values in `gateway.bind` (`auto`, `loopback`, `lan`, `tailnet`, `custom`), not host aliases (`0.0.0.0`, `127.0.0.1`, `localhost`, `::`, `::1`).\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/gateway/configuration-reference.md:432:- **Docker note**: the default `loopback` bind listens on `127.0.0.1` inside the container. With Docker bridge networking (`-p 18789:18789`), traffic arrives on `eth0`, so the gateway is unreachable. Use `--network host`, or set `bind: \"lan\"` (or `bind: \"custom\"` with `customBindHost: \"0.0.0.0\"`) to listen on all interfaces.\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/gateway/configuration-reference.md:640:      serve: { bind: \"127.0.0.1\", port: 8788, path: \"/\" },\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/gateway/configuration-reference.md:669:- Local-only: keep `gateway.bind: \"loopback\"` (default).\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/gateway/troubleshooting.md:288:    - `refusing to bind gateway ... without auth` → non-loopback bind without a valid gateway auth path (token/password, or trusted-proxy where configured).\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/gateway/troubleshooting.md:577:    openclaw config get gateway.bind\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/gateway/troubleshooting.md:591:    - `refusing to bind gateway ... without auth` → non-loopback bind without a valid gateway auth path.\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/gateway/network-model.md:22:    When `gateway.auth` is configured and the Gateway binds beyond loopback, these routes are protected by Gateway auth. Node clients use node-scoped capability URLs tied to their active WS session. See [Gateway configuration](/gateway/configuration) (`canvasHost`, `gateway`).\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/gateway/bonjour.md:39:  gateway: { bind: \"tailnet\" }, // tailnet-only (recommended)\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/gateway/bonjour.md:79:- Set `gateway.bind: \"tailnet\"` in `~/.openclaw/openclaw.json`.\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/gateway/bonjour.md:216:- Disabling Bonjour does not change `gateway.bind`; Docker still defaults to\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/gateway/bonjour.md:290:- `gateway.bind` in `~/.openclaw/openclaw.json` controls the Gateway bind mode.\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/gateway/bridge-protocol.md:77:- Bind the bridge to a tailnet IP: `bridge.bind: \"tailnet\"` in\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/gateway/remote.md:26:- **Best UX:** keep `gateway.bind: \"loopback\"` and use **Tailscale Serve** for the Control UI.\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/gateway/tailscale.md:62:    bind: \"loopback\",\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/gateway/tailscale.md:77:    bind: \"tailnet\",\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/gateway/tailscale.md:97:    bind: \"loopback\",\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/gateway/tailscale.md:119:- `gateway.bind: \"tailnet\"` is a direct Tailnet bind (no HTTPS, no Serve/Funnel).\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/gateway/tailscale.md:120:- `gateway.bind: \"auto\"` prefers loopback; use `tailnet` if you want Tailnet-only.\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/gateway/configuration-examples.md:425:      serve: { bind: \"127.0.0.1\", port: 8788, path: \"/\" },\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/gateway/configuration-examples.md:434:    bind: \"loopback\",\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/gateway/index.md:113:| Bind mode    | CLI/override → `gateway.bind` → `loopback`                    |\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/gateway/index.md:384:| `refusing to bind gateway ... without auth`                    | Non-loopback bind without a valid gateway auth path                             |\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/gateway/sandboxing.md:358:- See [Sandbox vs Tool Policy vs Elevated](/gateway/sandbox-vs-tool-policy-vs-elevated) for how binds interact with tool policy and elevated exec.\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/gateway/doctor.md:419:    When `openclaw doctor --fix` removes a missing channel plugin, it also removes the dangling channel-scoped config that referenced that plugin: `channels.<id>` entries, heartbeat targets that named the channel, and `agents.*.models[\"<channel>/*\"]` overrides. This prevents Gateway boot loops where the channel runtime is gone but config still asks the gateway to bind to it.\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/tools/diffs.md:394:- If gateway bind mode is `custom` and `gateway.customBindHost` is set, that host is used.\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/tools/diffs.md:468:      - use `gateway.bind=custom` and `gateway.customBindHost`\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/help/faq-first-run.md:123:    - **Tailnet bind**: run `openclaw gateway --bind tailnet --token \"***\"` (or configure password auth), open `http://<tailscale-ip>:18789/`, then paste the matching shared secret in dashboard settings.\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/help/faq.md:479:    See [Sandboxing](/gateway/sandboxing#custom-bind-mounts) and [Sandbox vs Tool Policy vs Elevated](/gateway/sandbox-vs-tool-policy-vs-elevated#bind-mounts-security-quick-check) for examples and safety notes.\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/help/faq.md:668:  <Accordion title='I set gateway.bind: \"lan\" (or \"tailnet\") and now nothing listens / the UI says unauthorized'>\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/help/faq.md:677:        bind: \"lan\",\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/help/faq.md:1482:  <Accordion title=\"I set gateway.bind tailnet but it cannot bind and nothing listens\">\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/help/faq.md:1488:    - Switch to `gateway.bind: \"loopback\"` / `\"lan\"`.\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/help/faq.md:1490:    Note: `tailnet` is explicit. `auto` prefers loopback; use `gateway.bind: \"tailnet\"` when you want a tailnet-only bind.\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/help/testing-live.md:217:- Test: `src/gateway/gateway-acp-bind.live.test.ts`\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/help/testing-live.md:224:  - `pnpm test:live src/gateway/gateway-acp-bind.live.test.ts`\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/help/testing-live.md:254:  pnpm test:live src/gateway/gateway-acp-bind.live.test.ts\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/help/testing-live.md:266:pnpm test:docker:live-acp-bind:claude\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/help/testing-live.md:267:pnpm test:docker:live-acp-bind:codex\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/help/testing-live.md:268:pnpm test:docker:live-acp-bind:droid\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/help/testing-live.md:269:pnpm test:docker:live-acp-bind:gemini\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/help/testing-live.md:270:pnpm test:docker:live-acp-bind:opencode\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/help/testing-live.md:280:- The OpenCode Docker variant is a strict single-agent regression lane. It writes a temporary `OPENCODE_CONFIG_CONTENT` default model from `OPENCLAW_LIVE_ACP_BIND_OPENCODE_MODEL` (default `opencode/kimi-k2.6`) after sourcing `~/.profile`, and `pnpm test:docker:live-acp-bind:opencode` requires a bound assistant transcript instead of accepting the generic post-bind skip.\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/help/troubleshooting.md:198:    - `refusing to bind gateway ... without auth` → non-loopback bind without a valid gateway auth path (token/password, or trusted-proxy where configured).\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/help/debugging.md:217:   - Writes a minimal config if missing (`gateway.mode=local`, bind loopback).\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/help/testing.md:636:- ACP bind smoke: `pnpm test:docker:live-acp-bind` (script: `scripts/test-live-acp-bind-docker.sh`; covers Claude, Codex, and Gemini by default, with strict Droid/OpenCode coverage via `pnpm test:docker:live-acp-bind:droid` and `pnpm test:docker:live-acp-bind:opencode`)\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/platforms/digitalocean.md:108:The gateway binds to loopback by default. To access the Control UI:\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/platforms/digitalocean.md:141:openclaw config set gateway.bind tailnet\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/platforms/mac/bundled-gateway.md:66:openclaw gateway --port 18999 --bind loopback\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/platforms/oracle.md:116:openclaw config set gateway.bind loopback\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/platforms/ios.md:102:- If the app later connects to a different gateway or a build with a different relay base URL, it refreshes the relay registration instead of reusing the old binding.\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/platforms/android.md:58:For remote Android access over Tailscale, prefer Serve/Funnel instead of a raw tailnet bind:\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/platforms/android.md:64:This gives Android a secure `wss://` / `https://` endpoint. A plain `gateway.bind: \"tailnet\"` setup is not enough for first-time remote Android pairing unless you also terminate TLS separately.\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/cli/security.md:87:- change gateway bind/auth/network exposure choices\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/ci.md:232:Docker-backed live model/backend shards use a separate shared `ghcr.io/openclaw/openclaw-live-test:<sha>` image per selected commit. The live release workflow builds and pushes that image once, then the Docker live model, provider-sharded gateway, CLI backend, ACP bind, and Codex harness shards run with `OPENCLAW_SKIP_DOCKER_BUILD=1`. Gateway Docker shards carry explicit script-level `timeout` caps below the workflow job timeout so a stuck container or cleanup path fails fast instead of consuming the whole release-check budget. If those shards rebuild the full source Docker target independently, the release run is misconfigured and will waste wall clock on duplicate image builds.\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/nodes/troubleshooting.md:81:For approval-backed `host=node` runs, the gateway also binds execution to the\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/nodes/index.md:90:### Remote gateway via SSH tunnel (loopback bind)\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/nodes/index.md:92:If the Gateway binds to loopback (`gateway.bind=loopback`, default in local mode),\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/gateway/configuration.md:492:    See [Multi-Agent](/concepts/multi-agent) and [full reference](/gateway/config-agents#multi-agent-routing) for binding rules and per-agent access profiles.\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/gateway/configuration.md:577:| Gateway server      | `gateway.*` (port, bind, auth, tailscale, TLS, HTTP)              | **Yes**         |\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/gateway/gateway-lock.md:19:- The gateway then binds the HTTP/WebSocket listener (default `ws://127.0.0.1:18789`) using an exclusive TCP listener.\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/gateway/gateway-lock.md:32:- The macOS app still maintains its own lightweight PID guard before spawning the gateway; the runtime lock is enforced by the lock file plus HTTP/WebSocket bind.\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/gateway/discovery.md:22:- **Gateway WS (control plane)**: the WebSocket endpoint on `127.0.0.1:18789` by default; can be bound to LAN/tailnet via `gateway.bind`.\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/gateway/discovery.md:98:- `gateway.bind` in `~/.openclaw/openclaw.json` controls the Gateway bind mode.\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/gateway/trusted-proxy-auth.md:68:    bind: \"lan\",\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/gateway/trusted-proxy-auth.md:187:        bind: \"lan\",\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/gateway/trusted-proxy-auth.md:221:        bind: \"lan\",\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/gateway/trusted-proxy-auth.md:253:        bind: \"lan\",\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/gateway/trusted-proxy-auth.md:285:        bind: \"lan\",\n/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/gateway/security/audit-checks.md:37:| `gateway.bind_no_auth`                                        | critical      | Remote bind without shared secret                                                    | `gateway.bind`, `gateway.auth.*`                                                                     | no       |[... 1500 more characters truncated]"}],"details":{"persistedDetailsTruncated":true,"originalDetailsBytesAtLeast":8193,"originalDetailKeys":["status","exitCode","durationMs","aggregated","cwd"],"status":"completed","cwd":"/root/.openclaw/workspace","exitCode":0},"isError":false,"timestamp":1778720238263}}
{"type":"message","id":"9f851240","parentId":"674d4774","timestamp":"2026-05-14T00:57:20.974Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_lc8RR4vJUYoClREnBV0Dwwlm|fc_094b6994f4566fc6016a051defda648194be91730d114d37a0","name":"read","arguments":{"path":"/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/gateway/configuration-reference.md","offset":350,"limit":100}}],"api":"openai-codex-responses","provider":"openai-codex","model":"gpt-5.5","usage":{"input":5136,"output":39,"cacheRead":34304,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":39479,"cost":{"input":0.02568,"output":0.00117,"cacheRead":0.017152,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0.044002}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1778720238268,"responseId":"resp_094b6994f4566fc6016a051def092c8194a1210d89d129cbf1"}}
{"type":"message","id":"12f23fd8","parentId":"9f851240","timestamp":"2026-05-14T00:57:20.980Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_lc8RR4vJUYoClREnBV0Dwwlm|fc_094b6994f4566fc6016a051defda648194be91730d114d37a0","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"- `assistant`: Control UI identity override. Falls back to active agent identity.\n\n---\n\n## Gateway\n\n```json5\n{\n  gateway: {\n    mode: \"local\", // local | remote\n    port: 18789,\n    bind: \"loopback\",\n    auth: {\n      mode: \"token\", // none | token | password | trusted-proxy\n      token: \"your-token\",\n      // password: \"your-password\", // or OPENCLAW_GATEWAY_PASSWORD\n      // trustedProxy: { userHeader: \"x-forwarded-user\" }, // for mode=trusted-proxy; see /gateway/trusted-proxy-auth\n      allowTailscale: true,\n      rateLimit: {\n        maxAttempts: 10,\n        windowMs: 60000,\n        lockoutMs: 300000,\n        exemptLoopback: true,\n      },\n    },\n    tailscale: {\n      mode: \"off\", // off | serve | funnel\n      resetOnExit: false,\n    },\n    controlUi: {\n      enabled: true,\n      basePath: \"/openclaw\",\n      // root: \"dist/control-ui\",\n      // embedSandbox: \"scripts\", // strict | scripts | trusted\n      // allowExternalEmbedUrls: false, // dangerous: allow absolute external http(s) embed URLs\n      // chatMessageMaxWidth: \"min(1280px, 82%)\", // optional grouped chat message max-width\n      // allowedOrigins: [\"https://control.example.com\"], // required for non-loopback Control UI\n      // dangerouslyAllowHostHeaderOriginFallback: false, // dangerous Host-header origin fallback mode\n      // allowInsecureAuth: false,\n      // dangerouslyDisableDeviceAuth: false,\n    },\n    remote: {\n      url: \"ws://gateway.tailnet:18789\",\n      transport: \"ssh\", // ssh | direct\n      token: \"your-token\",\n      // password: \"your-password\",\n    },\n    trustedProxies: [\"10.0.0.1\"],\n    // Optional. Default false.\n    allowRealIpFallback: false,\n    nodes: {\n      pairing: {\n        // Optional. Default unset/disabled.\n        autoApproveCidrs: [\"192.168.1.0/24\", \"fd00:1234:5678::/64\"],\n      },\n      allowCommands: [\"canvas.navigate\"],\n      denyCommands: [\"system.run\"],\n    },\n    tools: {\n      // Additional /tools/invoke HTTP denies\n      deny: [\"browser\"],\n      // Remove tools from the default HTTP deny list\n      allow: [\"gateway\"],\n    },\n    push: {\n      apns: {\n        relay: {\n          baseUrl: \"https://relay.example.com\",\n          timeoutMs: 10000,\n        },\n      },\n    },\n  },\n}\n```\n\n<Accordion title=\"Gateway field details\">\n\n- `mode`: `local` (run gateway) or `remote` (connect to remote gateway). Gateway refuses to start unless `local`.\n- `port`: single multiplexed port for WS + HTTP. Precedence: `--port` > `OPENCLAW_GATEWAY_PORT` > `gateway.port` > `18789`.\n- `bind`: `auto`, `loopback` (default), `lan` (`0.0.0.0`), `tailnet` (Tailscale IP only), or `custom`.\n- **Legacy bind aliases**: use bind mode values in `gateway.bind` (`auto`, `loopback`, `lan`, `tailnet`, `custom`), not host aliases (`0.0.0.0`, `127.0.0.1`, `localhost`, `::`, `::1`).\n- **Docker note**: the default `loopback` bind listens on `127.0.0.1` inside the container. With Docker bridge networking (`-p 18789:18789`), traffic arrives on `eth0`, so the gateway is unreachable. Use `--network host`, or set `bind: \"lan\"` (or `bind: \"custom\"` with `customBindHost: \"0.0.0.0\"`) to listen on all interfaces.\n- **Auth**: required by default. Non-loopback binds require gateway auth. In practice that means a shared token/password or an identity-aware reverse proxy with `gateway.auth.mode: \"trusted-proxy\"`. Onboarding wizard generates a token by default.\n- If both `gateway.auth.token` and `gateway.auth.password` are configured (including SecretRefs), set `gateway.auth.mode` explicitly to `token` or `password`. Startup and service install/repair flows fail when both are configured and mode is unset.\n- `gateway.auth.mode: \"none\"`: explicit no-auth mode. Use only for trusted local loopback setups; this is intentionally not offered by onboarding prompts.\n- `gateway.auth.mode: \"trusted-proxy\"`: delegate browser/user auth to an identity-aware reverse proxy and trust identity headers from `gateway.trustedProxies` (see [Trusted Proxy Auth](/gateway/trusted-proxy-auth)). This mode expects a **non-loopback** proxy source by default; same-host loopback reverse proxies require explicit `gateway.auth.trustedProxy.allowLoopback = true`. Internal same-host callers can use `gateway.auth.password` as a local direct fallback; `gateway.auth.token` remains mutually exclusive with trusted-proxy mode.\n- `gateway.auth.allowTailscale`: when `true`, Tailscale Serve identity headers can satisfy Control UI/WebSocket auth (verified via `tailscale whois`). HTTP API endpoints do **not** use that Tailscale header auth; they follow the gateway's normal HTTP auth mode instead. This tokenless flow assumes the gateway host is trusted. Defaults to `true` when `tailscale.mode = \"serve\"`.\n- `gateway.auth.rateLimit`: optional failed-auth limiter. Applies per client IP and per auth scope (shared-secret and device-token are tracked independently). Blocked attempts return `429` + `Retry-After`.\n  - On the async Tailscale Serve Control UI path, failed attempts for the same `{scope, clientIp}` are serialized before the failure write. Concurrent bad attempts from the same client can therefore trip the limiter on the second request instead of both racing through as plain mismatches.\n  - `gateway.auth.rateLimit.exemptLoopback` defaults to `true`; set `false` when you intentionally want localhost traffic rate-limited too (for test setups or strict proxy deployments).\n- Browser-origin WS auth attempts are always throttled with loopback exemption disabled (defense-in-depth against browser-based localhost brute force).\n- On loopback, those browser-origin lockouts are isolated per normalized `Origin`\n  value, so repeated failures from one localhost origin do not automatically\n  lock out a different origin.\n- `tailscale.mode`: `serve` (tailnet only, loopback bind) or `funnel` (public, requires auth).\n- `controlUi.allowedOrigins`: explicit browser-origin allowlist for Gateway WebSocket connects. Required when browser clients are expected from non-loopback origins.\n- `controlUi.chatMessageMaxWidth`: optional max-width for grouped Control UI chat messages. Accepts constrained CSS width values such as `960px`, `82%`, `min(1280px, 82%)`, and `calc(100% - 2rem)`.\n- `controlUi.dangerouslyAllowHostHeaderOriginFallback`: dangerous mode that enables Host-header origin fallback for deployments that intentionally rely on Host-header origin policy.\n- `remote.transport`: `ssh` (default) or `direct` (ws/wss). For `direct`, `remote.url` must be `ws://` or `wss://`.\n\n[835 more lines in file. Use offset=450 to continue.]"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1778720240979}}
